  "markdown_debrief": "### ⚡ SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n**📌 S – Set the Stage (The Verdict & Diagnostic Pivot)**\n- **The Verdict:** Option **A** (Right hepatectomy) is correct because if the marked area represents the future liver remnant (FLR) and consists of the left hepatic lobe (Couinaud segments II, III, and IV), then the surgical procedure required to achieve this remnant is the removal of the right hepatic lobe (Couinaud segments V, VI, VII, and VIII).\n- **The Pivot Point:** The understanding that the **\"marked area\" is the future liver remnant (FLR)**, implying the *resection* must be the *remaining* portion of the liver not included in the FLR. In this context, an FLR comprising the left lobe (segments II, III, IV) necessitates a **right hepatectomy**.\n\n---\n\n**🎯 H – Highlight Excellence (The Surgical \"Why\" & Pathology)**\n- **Surgical Mechanism:**\n    - A **right hepatectomy** involves the surgical removal of the right hepatic lobe, which includes Couinaud segments V, VI, VII, and VIII.\n    - The **future liver remnant (FLR)**, in this scenario, would consist of the left hepatic lobe (segments II, III, and IV).\n    - This procedure is typically performed for tumors or diseases primarily affecting the right lobe, while preserving sufficient functional liver parenchyma in the left lobe to prevent post-hepatectomy liver failure (PHLF).\n- **Clinical Execution:**\n    - This is the single best management path when disease is confined to the right lobe and the left lobe is healthy and of adequate volume to sustain liver function post-resection.\n    - **Preoperative assessment of FLR volume** is critical, often performed with CT volumetry, to ensure the remaining liver volume is sufficient (typically >20-25% for healthy livers, >30-40% for cirrhotic or chemotherapy-damaged livers).\n    - **Portal vein embolization (PVE)** may be performed preoperatively to induce hypertrophy of the FLR, particularly when the anticipated FLR volume is marginal.\n- **👁️ Mental Operative Theatre:**\n    - The surgeon identifies the **main portal vein bifurcation** and the **right hepatic artery** and **right hepatic duct** within the porta hepatis.\n    - The **right hepatic vein** is identified and ligated/stapled at its confluence with the inferior vena cava.\n    - The **transection plane** is typically along Cantlie's line, which runs from the gallbladder fossa to the inferior vena cava, separating the right and left functional lobes.\n    - The **right lobe** is mobilized by dividing its peritoneal attachments (e.g., right triangular ligament, coronary ligament).\n    - The parenchyma is divided using various techniques (e.g., crush-clamp, CUSA, LigaSure) while carefully controlling vascular and biliary structures.\n\n---\n\n**❌ A – Address the Gaps (Systematic Distractor Demolition)**\n- **Option B (Extended right hepatectomy/right trisectionectomy) (Incorrect):**\n    - This procedure involves removal of the right lobe (segments V, VI, VII, VIII) *plus* segment IV (medial left lobe).\n    - It would be indicated if the disease extended into segment IV, and the FLR would then be segments II and III only.\n    - This option is incorrect because the FLR described (left lobe, segments II, III, IV) implies segment IV is *preserved*, not resected.\n- **Option C (Left hepatectomy) (Incorrect):**\n    - This procedure involves removal of the left lobe (segments II, III, IV).\n    - It would be indicated if the disease was confined to the left lobe, and the FLR would be the right lobe (segments V, VI, VII, VIII).\n    - This option is incorrect because the question states the *marked area* (FLR) is the left lobe, meaning the left lobe is *preserved*, not resected.\n- **Option D (Extended left hepatectomy/left trisectionectomy) (Incorrect):**\n    - This procedure involves removal of the left lobe (segments II, III, IV) *plus* segments V and/or VIII (medial right lobe).\n    - It would be indicated if the disease extended into the medial right lobe, and the FLR would then be segments VI and VII only.\n    - This option is incorrect as it implies resection of the left lobe, which is designated as the FLR.\n\n---\n\n**📊 R – Review Learning Points (Evidence-Based Framework)**\n- **Core Principle:** Understanding Couinaud's segmental anatomy of the liver is fundamental for planning hepatic resections and predicting the future liver remnant (FLR). The goal is always to achieve complete tumor resection with negative margins while preserving adequate functional liver volume.\n\n| Hepatectomy Type | Couinaud Segments Resected | Typical Future Liver Remnant (FLR) | Key Indication |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Right Hepatectomy** | V, VI, VII, VIII | II, III, IV (Left Lobe) | Disease confined to right lobe |\n| **Left Hepatectomy** | II, III, IV | V, VI, VII, VIII (Right Lobe) | Disease confined to left lobe |\n| **Extended Right Hepatectomy (Right Trisectionectomy)** | IV, V, VI, VII, VIII | II, III | Disease involving right lobe and segment IV |\n| **Extended Left Hepatectomy (Left Trisectionectomy)** | II, III, IV, V, VIII | VI, VII | Disease involving left lobe and segments V/VIII |\n| **Left Lateral Sectionectomy (Left Lobectomy)** | II, III | IV, V, VI, VII, VIII | Disease confined to left lateral segments |\n\n> **⚠️ Critical Guideline Updates & Textbook Conflicts**\n> - **Standard Textbooks (Sabiston / Schwartz):** Emphasize the importance of preoperative imaging (CT/MRI) for precise tumor localization, vascular anatomy, and FLR volumetry. The minimum FLR percentage is a critical determinant for resectability.\n> - **Society Guidelines (AHPBA / IHPBA):** Recommend multidisciplinary team discussion for complex liver resections. For patients with underlying liver disease (e.g., cirrhosis, steatosis, chemotherapy-induced liver injury), a higher FLR percentage (e.g., >30-40%) is often required to minimize the risk of post-hepatectomy liver failure.\n> - **The Discrepancy:** While the anatomical definitions are consistent, the *thresholds* for acceptable FLR and the strategies to achieve it (e.g., PVE, ALPPS) are continually evolving based on patient comorbidities and surgical advancements.\n\n---\n\n**💡 P – Plan for Improvement (The Exam Heuristic)**\n- **The Board Pearl:** If the \"future liver remnant\" is the left lobe (segments II, III, IV), then the \"resection to be performed\" is a right hepatectomy."
