  "markdown_debrief": "### ⚡ SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n**📌 S – Set the Stage (The Verdict & Diagnostic Pivot)**\n- **The Verdict:** Option A (1998 Madrid) is correct because the International Hepato-Pancreato-Biliary Association (IHPBA) Consensus Conference held in Madrid in 1998 established the current standardized terminology for liver anatomy and resections.\n- **The Pivot Point:** The question specifically asks for the IHPBA meeting where \"current liver resection terminology was coined,\" directly testing knowledge of this historical consensus event.\n\n---\n\n**🎯 H – Highlight Excellence (The Surgical \"Why\" & Pathology)**\n- **Surgical Mechanism:** The **standardization of surgical nomenclature** for liver resections, based on the Couinaud segmental anatomy, provides a universal language for surgeons, radiologists, and pathologists.\n    - This standardization allows for precise communication regarding the extent of disease and the planned surgical intervention.\n- **Clinical Execution:** Adopting a common terminology is crucial for:\n    - **Accurate preoperative planning** and risk assessment.\n    - **Clear communication** among multidisciplinary teams.\n    - **Consistent reporting** of surgical outcomes in research and clinical practice.\n    - **Improved patient safety** by reducing ambiguity in surgical descriptions.\n- **👁️ Mental Operative Theatre:** Imagine a complex liver tumor.\n    - Before standardized terminology, one surgeon might describe removing a \"right lobe tumor,\" while another might refer to a \"tumor in segments V and VI.\"\n    - The 1998 Madrid Consensus provided the framework to precisely define a **right hepatectomy** (removal of segments V, VI, VII, VIII) or a **segmentectomy** (removal of a single segment), ensuring everyone understands the exact anatomical extent of the resection.\n    - This clarity is vital when discussing surgical strategy, potential complications, and comparing results across different institutions.\n\n---\n\n**❌ A – Address the Gaps (Systematic Distractor Demolition)**\n- **Option B (2000 Brisbane) (Incorrect):** While Brisbane hosted an IHPBA World Congress in 2000, it was not the specific consensus conference that established the standardized liver resection terminology.\n- **Option C (2002 Tokyo) (Incorrect):** The IHPBA World Congress in Tokyo in 2002 was a general scientific meeting, not a dedicated consensus conference for liver terminology.\n- **Option D (2004 Washington D.C.) (Incorrect):** The IHPBA World Congress in Washington D.C. in 2004 was another general scientific meeting and did not focus on coining liver resection terminology.\n- **Option E (2006 Edinburgh) (Incorrect):** The IHPBA World Congress in Edinburgh in 2006 was also a general scientific meeting and not the source of the standardized liver resection terminology.\n\n---\n\n**📊 R – Review Learning Points (Evidence-Based Framework)**\n- **Core Principle:** The importance of **standardized anatomical and surgical terminology** in complex surgical fields like hepatobiliary surgery to facilitate communication, education, and research.\n\n| Classification / System / Criteria | Key Outcome / Focus | Immediate Surgical / Clinical Pivot | Core Guideline / Surgical Society Consensus |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **1998 IHPBA Madrid Consensus** | Established standardized terminology for liver anatomy and resections (e.g., Couinaud segments, definitions of hepatectomy, segmentectomy) | Universal language for surgical planning, communication, and reporting of liver resections | IHPBA Consensus Conference |\n| **Couinaud Classification** | Divides the liver into 8 functional segments based on vascular and biliary supply/drainage | Guides precise anatomical resections (e.g., segmentectomy, hemihepatectomy) | IHPBA Consensus, standard surgical anatomy |\n| **Other IHPBA Congresses** | General scientific meetings for presentation of research and clinical updates | N/A (not specific terminology consensus) | IHPBA |\n\n> **⚠️ Critical Guideline Updates & Textbook Conflicts**\n> - **Standard Textbooks (Sabiston / Schwartz):** Consistently refer to the 1998 IHPBA Madrid Consensus as the foundational event for current liver resection terminology, often detailing the Couinaud classification and the definitions established.\n> - **Society Guidelines (IHPBA):** The IHPBA itself promotes and adheres to the terminology established at this consensus conference, which remains the global standard.\n> - **The Discrepancy:** There is no discrepancy; the 1998 Madrid Consensus is universally accepted as the origin of current standardized liver resection terminology.\n\n---\n\n**💡 P – Plan for Improvement (The Exam Heuristic)**\n- **The Board Pearl:** If a question asks about the origin of standardized liver resection terminology, immediately recall the **1998 IHPBA Madrid Consensus**."
