  "markdown_debrief": "### ⚡ SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n**📌 S – Set the Stage (The Verdict & Diagnostic Pivot)**\n- **The Verdict:** Option A (90%) is provided as the correct answer.\n- **The Pivot Point:** The question asks for the **minimum percent of future liver remnant (FLR)** typically needed to allow for extended lobectomy or trisectionectomy in a healthy adult.\n\n**🎯 H – Highlight Excellence (The Surgical \"Why\" & Pathology)**\n- **Surgical Mechanism:** The concept of **future liver remnant (FLR)** is paramount in planning major liver resections to prevent **post-hepatectomy liver failure (PHLF)**, a life-threatening complication. The liver has remarkable regenerative capacity, but a critical minimum volume of healthy parenchyma is required to sustain life.\n- **Clinical Execution:**\n    - Accurate pre-operative assessment of FLR is crucial.\n    - This is typically performed using **volumetric CT or MRI scans** to calculate the percentage of the total liver volume that will remain after resection.\n    - If the calculated FLR is insufficient, strategies such as **portal vein embolization (PVE)** or **associating liver partition and portal vein ligation for staged hepatectomy (ALPPS)** may be employed to induce hypertrophy of the remnant liver before definitive resection.\n- **👁️ Mental Operative Theatre:**\n    - The surgeon meticulously reviews pre-operative imaging, visualizing the tumor's location relative to major vascular and biliary structures.\n    - **Volumetric analysis** provides a precise \"roadmap\" of the liver, highlighting the planned resection lines and the estimated volume of the remaining liver.\n    - The goal is to ensure that the remaining liver parenchyma is not only sufficient in volume but also healthy and well-perfused to prevent functional compromise.\n\n**❌ A – Address the Gaps (Systematic Distractor Demolition)**\n- **Option B (70%) (Incorrect):** A 70% FLR would mean only 30% of the liver was resected. While this is a very safe remnant, an \"extended lobectomy or trisectionectomy\" typically involves resecting a much larger proportion of the liver (e.g., 60-85%).\n- **Option C (50%) (Incorrect):** A 50% FLR would mean 50% of the liver was resected. This is a substantial resection, but still generally less than what defines an extended lobectomy or trisectionectomy, which often removes 60-85% of the liver.\n- **Option D (25%) (Incorrect, but clinically most plausible):** A 25% FLR is the **standard minimum recommended for healthy adults** undergoing major hepatectomy (including extended lobectomy or trisectionectomy) according to current surgical guidelines. This option is incorrect *according to the provided answer key*, but represents the widely accepted clinical practice.\n- **Option E (10%) (Incorrect):** A 10% FLR is generally considered **insufficient** for survival after major hepatectomy, even in healthy individuals, and carries an extremely high risk of post-hepatectomy liver failure.\n\n**📊 R – Review Learning Points (Evidence-Based Framework)**\n- **Core Principle:** The **minimum future liver remnant (FLR)** required for safe major hepatectomy is a critical determinant of surgical candidacy and depends significantly on the underlying health and functional reserve of the liver.\n\n| Liver Health Status | Minimum FLR (Percent of Total Liver Volume) | Risk of PHLF if FLR < Threshold | Immediate Surgical / Clinical Pivot | Core Guideline / Surgical Society Consensus |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Healthy Liver** | **>20-25%** | Low if >20-25% | Proceed with resection if FLR adequate | SAGES, AHPBA, IHPBA |\n| **Chemotherapy-Treated Liver** | **>30%** | Moderate if <30% | Consider PVE/ALPPS if FLR <30% | SAGES, AHPBA, IHPBA |\n| **Cirrhotic / Steatotic Liver** | **>40%** | High if <40% | Strongly consider PVE/ALPPS if FLR <40% | SAGES, AHPBA, IHPBA |\n| **Biliary Obstruction / Cholangitis** | **>30-40%** | High if <30-40% | Decompress biliary system, consider PVE | SAGES, AHPBA, IHPBA |\n\n> **⚠️ Critical Guideline Updates & Textbook Conflicts**\n> - **Standard Textbooks (Sabiston / Schwartz):** Standard surgical texts and guidelines (e.g., SAGES, AHPBA, IHPBA) consistently recommend a **minimum future liver remnant (FLR) of 20-25% for healthy adults** undergoing major hepatectomy (including extended lobectomy or trisectionectomy).\n> - **Society Guidelines (AHPBA / IHPBA):** The consensus is that an FLR of 20-25% is generally sufficient for healthy patients, while higher percentages (30-40% or more) are required for patients with underlying liver disease or chemotherapy-induced injury.\n> - **The Discrepancy:** The provided correct answer of **90% FLR** is highly unusual and **contradicts established surgical guidelines and clinical practice**. A 90% FLR would imply that only 10% of the liver was resected, which does not constitute an \"extended lobectomy or trisectionectomy\" (these procedures typically remove 60-85% of the liver, leaving a 15-40% remnant). It is possible the question or the provided answer key is erroneous, or there is a highly specific, non-standard interpretation intended. Based on current evidence, Option D (25%) would be the clinically correct answer for a healthy adult.\n\n**💡 P – Plan for Improvement (The Board Pearl)**\n- **The Board Pearl:** \"For major liver resections in healthy adults, a future liver remnant of at least 20-25% is typically required to prevent post-hepatectomy liver failure.\""
